gmd:abstract.gco:CharacterString: Bedrock topography was converted from the original published map, Indiana Geological Survey Miscellaneous Map 36. The contours define the elevation/topography of the bedrock surface in Indiana.

gmd:purpose.gco:CharacterString: This shapefile was created to provide a GIS data layer of the bedrock topography in Indiana.

gmd:environmentDescription.gco:CharacterString: Windows 2000 operating system; ESRI ArcGIS 8.3 shapefile; approximately 4.1 MB

gmd:measureDescription.gco:CharacterString: No checks were made to identify dangling nodes or pseudo nodes; contours that did not reach the IGS PLSS state boundary (UTM Zone 16, NAD 83) were left as digitized and were not extended so that they accurately recreate the lines as drawn on IGS Miscellaneous Map 36.
Contour lines were completed across gaps left where elevation value text was placed on original map.

Indiana Geological Survey employees performed visual inspection of all topography lines and elevation values and compared them with the paper copies of the Map of Indiana Showing Topography of the Bedrock Surface, Indiana Geological Survey Miscellaneous Maps 36 and 35.

Accuracy is no better than that of the source material. Contour lines were omitted in areas of highest congestion due to scale and legibility of the original map. The digital data was tested using digital data compared on-screen with the scan of the paper map and with the paper copies of IGS Miscellaneous Maps 36 and 35.
The accuracy of elevation values is unknown.

gmd:description.gco:CharacterString: The scribed negative overlay used to create the offset-printed version of IGS Miscellaneous Map 36 was photographically imaged onto frosted mylar media. This mylar was scanned at a resolution of 600 dpi to the file BRKTOPO_600B.TIF. The resulting TIF file was displayed in ESRI ArcInfo 8.2, using ArcScan, and contour lines were autotraced with manual oversight and correction, where necessary, to create a temporary ArcInfo coverage. Reference tics from Miscellaneous Map 36 were used to georeference the coverage to UTM Zone 16, NAD83. The coverage was then converted to the ESRI ArcView 3.2 shapefile IN_BDRKTOPO_UTM.
IN_BDRKTOPO_UTM was opened in ESRI ArcView 3.3 and contour lines were attributed with elevation values, using IGS Miscellaneous Map 36 as the source of values.

Indiana Geological Survey employees then visually checked IN_BDRKTOPO_UTM.SHP on-screen against IGS Miscellaneous Map 36 to check for accuracy of attributes and lines. Based on these reviews, corrections were made to the shapefile in ESRI ArcView 3.3 using IGS Miscellaneous Map 36 and Miscellaneous Map 35 for reference. One contour line was found to be missing from the shapefile. To add this contour, the shapefile was converted into a coverage using ESRI ArcToolbox and displayed in ESRI ArcMap 8.2. The original TIF file was also brought in and georeferenced to fit the contours. The additional contour was added by manually digitization. Topology was built and the coverage was converted back into a shapefile using ESRI ArcToolbox. Extraneous fields were deleted from the shapefile using the Editor tool in ESRI ArcView 3.3.

Using the "GeoProcessing Wizard" in ESRI ArcMap 8.3, the shapefile was clipped to the boundary of Indiana using the shapefile LANDSURVEY_STATE_POLY_IN.SHP. The clipped shapefile was saved as BEDROCK_TOPOGRAPHY_MM36_IN.SHP.

This metadata file was pre-parsed and parsed using CNS (Chew and Spit, v. 2.6.1) and MP (Metadata Parser, v. 2.7.1) software written by Peter N. Schweitzer (United States Geological Survey). The errors generated by MP were all addressed and corrected, except that no values were assigned to "Abscissa_Resolution" and "Ordinate_Resolution."
Bedrock topography elevation contours and values

gmd:otherCitationDetails.gco:CharacterString: Two versions of this map are available. IGS Miscellaneous Map 35 has contours that are supplemented by colors; these colors are not present on IGS Miscellaneous Map 36.
